## The Glyph Threshold

The session opened where Session 3 ended: the Council of 8 in their crescent of root-carved thrones, Rootspire's amber light bleeding through living walls, the air tasting of old sap and something older still. A vertical seam split the floor of the chamber, and pale Veil-light poured upward — thin, overexposed, humming at a frequency the bones understood before the mind could.

Eight burning sigils materialized in the air before the party, each slowly rotating, each unlabelled. The Council spoke in unison: *"Know us."*

The party solved the glyph puzzle — shrewdly drawing on details recalled from the trial in Session 3. It was not brute intuition but accumulated knowledge, a reward for paying attention across sessions. The portal opened.

There was a beat of hesitation. The aperture beyond showed no landscape — only shifting pale geometry and the faint silhouettes of enormous shapes, indistinct and watching. One by one, the party stepped through.

---

## The Council Chamber

Inside, the chamber was not physically coherent. Distance, scale, and orientation shifted depending on who spoke. Eight presences manifested — not seated, not standing. Simply there.

The Council delivered the mandate: investigate the Veil anomalies forming beyond Orrenval's reach. Observe. Do not attempt repair. Bring back patterns, not solutions. The party was being sent because they had already survived exposure, because they were not yet politically entangled — and because their loss, while regrettable, would not destabilize the Concord. That last point was never stated aloud.

When one party member asked the prudent question — *"What should we be doing when we get to these anomalies?"* — the chamber shifted.

A presence that had until now remained silent surged forward. The one known as The Whispering Mask.

> *"PURIFY THEM."*

The word landed like a verdict. Sinister. Absolute.

A beat of silence. Then:

> *"Silence. You are on this council. But you are not granted the power to speak."*

The Veil Watcher. Measured. Final.

The Whispering Mask did not respond. The chamber retoned itself. But the players now knew something they had not known thirty seconds before: the Council is fractured, one of its members holds a philosophy the others actively suppress, and the word *"purify"* means something the rest of the Council does not want spoken aloud.

---

## Jaihroquai

Before the dismissal, the Council condensed a cluster of sigils into a single object and let it fall into the party's possession: the Anomaly Reliquary — a palm-sized disc of dark matte metal, its surface etched with incomplete sigils, a thin vertical seam at its center that trembles like a compass needle listening for something deeper than north.

Fergie attuned to it. During a short rest, the hum of the disc aligned with Fergie's internal heat — the seam sharpened, the rings stilled. The bond was formed. And in that stillness, the relic made itself known: its name is Jaihroquai.

Small flames near Fergie now flicker faintly toward Veil sources. A fire burning at the edge of something it cannot name.

One additional detail emerged: Jaihroquai does not much care about Hog. Hog is aware of this. Hog wants Jaihroquai's approval desperately. Jaihroquai remains indifferent.

---

## The Silence After

The chamber ejected the party. Sound returned first. Then weight. Then gravity. The portal collapsed to nothing, leaving only a faint heat-shimmer in the air that faded before anyone could focus on it. The cosmic oversight was gone. Whatever protection the Council's presence had offered — it was simply absent now.

The party returned to Rootspire. The Great Tree did not pause for revelation. The city moved, traded, laughed. Whatever the Council knew — this place did not.

---

## The Split Bark Tavern

The party found The Split Bark: warm, loud, lived-in. Ceiling curved like the inside of a hollow trunk. A chalk circle on the center floor. Coins clinking. Someone shouting *"Next pair in!"*

Hog and Zennor stepped into the circle. They fought. The crowd had opinions about the evening's entertainment — some more enthusiastic than others. Both ordered two Moss-Foam Lagers — the second-cheapest option, earthy and crisp.

They long-rested there.

---

## Tumor

On their way out, the party encountered Timoor — a figure near a moss-wrapped market stall, examining a cracked seedpod, tilting his head at angles that suggested a different relationship with necks than most people have.

Someone misheard the name as Tumor. Whether it sticks remains to be seen.

Wanting to determine whether Timoor was dangerous, the party interrogated him. Their questions were not conventional security screening. One party member asked his favourite colour. The other questions were of comparable forensic weight. One contribution was not a question at all: it was an instruction to punch Hog in the face.

The interrogation was inconclusive. Timoor's threat level remains unresolved.

Hog and Timoor nonetheless skipped off together merrily.

---

## The Notice Board

The party headed west toward the Spiral Loom — the direction Jaihroquai was pointing. Before they reached it, they found the Notice Board: bark-paper notices in charcoal and wax seal.

Among the postings: reports of an unidentified construct wandering the lower spiral, emitting faint geometric light. Reports of a woman walking through smoke untouched near the lower eastern roots. Sap collection crews refusing lower tunnel shifts and complaining of humming in the dark.

The party asked Timoor to join them, and decided to investigate the lower roots — drawn in particular by the notice about the construct.

---

## The Fire Spreads

Before the session closed, a rebel runner arrived. Breathless. Two of her riders had been lost on the road. She smelled of road dust and held herself like someone who had outrun something and wasn't sure she had outrun it far enough. But there was something underneath the fear — something that looked, faintly, like hope.

She carried a message cylinder, wax seal cracked clean through. The parchment smelled of ash. The script was hurried.

> *"Orrenval unrest escalating. Three districts ignited in protest following Captain Deyran's execution. Purity enforcement intensified. Minor insurrections suppressed. More expected."*

A final line, added in different ink:

> *"The fire sings louder than they can silence."*

The party engaged analytically. Questions came. The implications were not lost on them: their killing of Captain Deyran — a single act, violent, immediate, committed in Session 1 and fled from immediately — had moved into the city's blood and was now reshaping it from the inside. Protests. Singing. Districts alight. The Trifarix not unified in its response.

They did not start a revolution. They removed a keystone. The arch is shifting.

